{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QCQoGSDPkAgTiAsByuMym7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see. The controller in `ingress-nginx` uses `--ingress-class=ingress-1` and `--controller-class=k8s.io/ingress-nginx-1`. The `otel-echo` ingress uses `ingressClassName: nginx`. This controller won't handle the `nginx` class.\n\nI need to either:\n1. Change the ingress class of `otel-echo` to `ingress-1`\n2. Or change the controller's ingress class to `nginx`\n\nSince the task says the ingress already routes `otel.example.com` to a healthy backend and requests succeed, I think the intended approach is to patch the `otel-echo` ingress to use `ingress-1` class OR patch the controller to also handle `nginx` class.\nWait, I'm realizing the test is hitting the controller directly at `ingress-nginx-controller.ingress-nginx.svc`, which watches the `ingress-1` class, but the `otel-echo` ingress declares `nginx` class. So the controller won't actually route this traffic. The task description says the ingress should already be routing to a healthy backend, which suggests maybe the controller is also watching the `nginx` class somehow, or I need to verify what's actually happening.\n\nThe real issue is that even if the request returns 404, the controller still logs it, and for trace IDs to appear in those logs, OTel needs to be enabled and actively processing the request. The trace ID will only populate if OTel instrumentation is working correctly.\n\nSince the `otel-echo` ingress isn't being routed by this controller, the controller won't inject trace context into the request. I should either patch the ingress to use the `ingress-1` class to match the controller, or update the controller to watch the `nginx` class instead. The cleanest path seems to be changing the ingress class and then configuring OTel settings on the controller. controller is to patch the ingress to use the `ingress-1` class that the existing controller is already watching, then add OTel configuration to that controller so the trace IDs appear in the access logs.\n\nFor ingress-nginx v1.14.x with native OTel support, I need to set the ConfigMap keys to enable OpenTelemetry with the collector endpoint, configure sampling to capture all requests, and set the service name for the nginx instance. I'm looking at the specific ConfigMap keys for ingress-nginx v1.14.x with native OpenTelemetry support, including the enable flag, sampler configuration, OTLP collector endpoint settings, and how to integrate trace IDs and span IDs into the upstream log format.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1324,"cache_read_input_tokens":35017,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1324},"output_tokens":44,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"10e8a98a-d99f-477f-a1d5-68ca81c27cd7","uuid":"235c91a3-cfe1-476b-93bb-491de2643c45","request_id":"req_011CcQUQ2LCVJsz6r9deY52X"}
