{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PmhTwzygPKuawDH7hp3ENa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the cfg.json doesn't have OTel keys yet (because OTel isn't enabled). Let me look at how the ingress-nginx controller handles its configuration to understand what ConfigMap keys map to what.\n\nLet me look at what keys the `buildOpentelemetry` template function generates. Actually, from my knowledge of ingress-nginx:\n\nThe ConfigMap keys for OTel in ingress-nginx v1.10+ are:\n- `enable-opentelemetry: \"true\"` → `cfg.EnableOpentelemetry`\n- `opentelemetry-config: /etc/nginx/opentelemetry.toml` → `cfg.OpentelemetryConfig`\n- `otel-sampler: \"AlwaysOn\"` → sampler type\n- `otel-sampler-ratio: \"1.0\"` → sampling ratio\n- `otel-sampler-parent-based: \"true\"` → parent based\n- `otel-service-name: \"nginx\"` → service name\n- `otlp-collector-host` and `otlp-collector-port: \"4317\"` → OTLP collector connection details\n\nNow I need to check the actual nginx template's `buildOpentelemetry` function to see what it's generating.\n\nLooking at the template, `opentelemetry_config` is a nginx directive pointing to a TOML file. The TOML format specifies the exporter endpoint, sampler configuration, and service name. I'm trying to figure out whether I can configure this entirely through ConfigMap or if I need to mount a separate TOML file.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":255,"cache_read_input_tokens":41843,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":255},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"10e8a98a-d99f-477f-a1d5-68ca81c27cd7","uuid":"517956e3-d077-4b84-9c21-4f2ce2516640","request_id":"req_011CcQUVZCUGTrxYQBYqFRjP"}
