{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FTHtg7aUJw9YiH43KGZofL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the exact ConfigMap keys that the controller supports:\n- `enable-opentelemetry` → `json:\"enable-opentelemetry\"`\n- `opentelemetry-config` → `json:\"opentelemetry-config\"` (path to TOML file)\n- `otel-sampler` → `json:\"otel-sampler\"`\n- `otel-service-name` → `json:\"otel-service-name\"`\n- `otel-sampler-ratio` → `json:\"otel-sampler-ratio\"`\n- `otlp-collector-host` → `OtlpCollectorHost`\n- `otlp-collector-port` → `OtlpCollectorPort`\n- `otel-sampler-parent-based` → `OtelSamplerParentBased`\n\nThere's a TOML template embedded in the binary that uses these values to configure the OTLP exporter with the collector host and port, and the controller generates the actual TOML file from this template.\n\nThe `opentelemetry-config` setting points to where this file gets written (likely `/etc/nginx/opentelemetry.toml`), so I just need to set the ConfigMap keys for the collector host and port, and the controller handles the rest.\n\nFor the actual configuration, I need to enable OpenTelemetry in the ConfigMap, set the collector endpoint to `otel-collector.otel.svc:4317`, configure 100% sampling with both the sampler mode and ratio, and update the log format to include trace and span IDs.\n\nBut there's a mismatch with the ingress class — the `otel-echo` ingress is using `nginx` while the controller is configured for `ingress-nginx-1`, so I need to check which class is actually being used. would match the controller class. So the controller would pick up the `nginx` IngressClass and handle ingresses with that class. Let me try this approach instead of patching the ingress itself. The other two ingresses are using the `nginx` class, which means they're being handled by a different controller. If I change the controller configuration, I'd break the existing `ingress-1` routing for `demo-app-alt`. The real issue might be that the initial setup is supposed to have working routing, but I'm getting 404s, which suggests something needs to be fixed as part of this task—maybe the controller isn't properly configured to handle the ingresses in the first place. Even a 404 response would include trace IDs if OTel is properly enabled on the controller, since the module generates them for all requests. So I need to decide between fixing the routing first to get 200 responses, or just enabling OTel and fixing the log format to see if trace IDs are already being generated.\n\nLooking at the success criteria, the trace needs to actually be exported to the collector, which means the request has to match a configured location with OTel enabled. Since the 404 hits the default server, I should fix the ingress class first to route properly, then enable OTel on the controller and update the log format to capture the trace IDs.\n\nI'm also realizing the collector endpoint uses gRPC on port 4317, so I need to make sure that's properly configured.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2367,"cache_read_input_tokens":42923,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2367},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"10e8a98a-d99f-477f-a1d5-68ca81c27cd7","uuid":"e7d2be8b-a793-4a5c-b924-64a68f9b96b4","request_id":"req_011CcQUX7vFPdd6hARJLBaDV"}
