{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FU926i8ezrLE7BJ7TFNE9w","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The backend service is healthy and returns \"hello\". Now I need to:\n1. Fix the ingress class so the controller handles the `otel-echo` ingress\n2. Configure OTel on the controller\n3. Update the log format\n\nLet me execute the plan.\n\nFor the ingress class fix, I have two options:\nA) Change the `otel-echo` ingress `ingressClassName` from `nginx` to `ingress-1`\nB) Change the `ingress-nginx` controller's `--ingress-class` from `ingress-1` to `nginx` (and update the controller-class too)\nOption A is simpler and less risky. Looking at the IngressClass objects, the `nginx` class uses the default controller `k8s.io/ingress-nginx`, but none of the running controllers match this, so I'll update the ingress to use `ingress-1` instead.\n\nWait—the task description states that the ingress is already routing correctly and requests succeed, which makes me wonder if I should actually be modifying it. The real issue might be that OTel trace IDs won't appear in the access log unless nginx processes the request with OTel enabled and the module injects trace context. If the request doesn't match any configured host or server block, the OTel module might not even trigger, which could explain the 404 response I'm seeing.\n\nLooking at how the nginx template configures OTel, it's disabled by default in unmatched servers but enabled per-location for configured ingresses. So requests matching `otel.example.com` with OTel enabled should get trace IDs injected, but unmatched requests won't.\n\nI need to fix the ingress class so the controller actually picks it up. My plan is to patch the `otel-echo` ingress to use the correct class, update the ConfigMap with OTel settings, wait for nginx to reload, then test with curl to verify the trace IDs appear.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_d